<subSubSection id="C3426532F934FFA0FCF4F9255612F176" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="627" pageId="1" pageNumber="626" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F934FFA0FCF4F9255612F176" blockId="1.[831,1474,1790,1974]" lastBlockId="2.[158,802,194,281]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="627" pageId="1" pageNumber="626">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF934FFA3FCF4F9255685F779" bold="true" box="[831,949,1791,1814]" pageId="1" pageNumber="626">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C584D3AF934FFA3FC76F9245106F779" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1871" box="[957,1078,1790,1814]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Physopyxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="626" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF934FFA3FC76F9245106F779" box="[957,1078,1790,1814]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="626">Physopyxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the other 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D3AF934FFA3FCF4F8C5569FF759" authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1858" box="[831,943,1823,1846]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="626" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Doradidae</taxonomicName>
by the miniature size (adults less than 
<quantity id="4CA09B5CF934FFA3FA81F8C550A4F759" box="[1354,1428,1823,1846]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="626" unit="mm" value="31.0">31 mm</quantity>
SL) and a unique combination of additional features: extreme development of the exposed pectoral girdle; well developed coracoid process longer than the postcleithral process; anterior plate of the nuchal shield absent; dorsal spine serrated only along the basal portion of its anterior margin; two infraorbital bones in young that become fused into a single plate in adult specimens; pectoral spine reaching to base of anal fin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3426532F937FFA0FF55FE9850F9F236" pageId="2" pageNumber="627" type="key">
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F937FFA0FF55FE9854DBF136" blockId="2.[158,801,322,601]" box="[158,491,322,346]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF937FFA0FF55FE9854D3F135" bold="true" box="[158,483,322,346]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
Key for species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D3AF937FFA0FEA3FE9854D3F135" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1871" box="[360,483,322,346]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Physopyxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="627" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF937FFA0FEA3FE9854D3F135" bold="true" box="[360,483,322,346]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Physopyxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F937FFA0FF55FEB85611F236" blockId="2.[158,801,322,601]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
1. Lateral line incomplete, with 5 to 12 lateral plates, each with one retrorse spine; a series of small spines along dorsal midline formed by the external expansion of the vertebral neural spines; adipose fin present (
<figureCitation id="13632A3CF937FFA0FDF3FE1857B5F1B6" box="[568,645,450,473]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[158,197,1919,1942]" captionTargetBox="[331,1310,622,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[321,1318,619,1904]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Diagnostic characters of the three species of Physopyxis. a. Physopyxis cristata; b. Physopyxis lyra; c. Physopyxis ananas; d. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. ananas and P. cristata; e. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. lyra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5418075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5418075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Fig. 2a</figureCitation>
) .... 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D3AF937FFA0FD7FFE185610F1B6" authorityName="Sousa &amp; Rapp Py-Daniel" authorityYear="2005" box="[692,800,450,473]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Physopyxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="627" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF937FFA0FD7FFE185610F1B6" box="[692,800,450,473]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">P. cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(rio Negro basin) 1'. Lateral line complete; lateral plates well developed to caudal fin and meeting dorsally in larger specimens; adipose fin present or absent (
<figureCitation id="13632A3CF937FFA0FE6AFD9854D8F236" box="[417,488,578,601]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[158,197,1919,1942]" captionTargetBox="[331,1310,622,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[321,1318,619,1904]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Diagnostic characters of the three species of Physopyxis. a. Physopyxis cristata; b. Physopyxis lyra; c. Physopyxis ananas; d. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. ananas and P. cristata; e. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. lyra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5418075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5418075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
b-c) ...................................... 2
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F937FFA0FC8CFF1850F9F156" blockId="2.[839,1482,194,377]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
2. Lateral plates with only one series of spines; superior wing of lateral plates deeper than inferior wing (
<figureCitation id="13632A3CF937FFA0FAFBFF38504FF096" box="[1328,1407,226,249]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[158,197,1919,1942]" captionTargetBox="[331,1310,622,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[321,1318,619,1904]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Diagnostic characters of the three species of Physopyxis. a. Physopyxis cristata; b. Physopyxis lyra; c. Physopyxis ananas; d. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. ananas and P. cristata; e. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. lyra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5418075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5418075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Fig. 2b</figureCitation>
); coracoid processes with posterior tip enlarged, knob-like and diverging laterally (
<figureCitation id="13632A3CF937FFA0FB88FEF851A2F156" box="[1091,1170,290,313]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[158,197,1919,1942]" captionTargetBox="[331,1310,622,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[321,1318,619,1904]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Diagnostic characters of the three species of Physopyxis. a. Physopyxis cristata; b. Physopyxis lyra; c. Physopyxis ananas; d. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. ananas and P. cristata; e. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. lyra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5418075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5418075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Fig. 2e</figureCitation>
); adipose fin usually present
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F937FFA0FCA7FE9850FAF136" blockId="2.[839,1482,194,377]" box="[876,1482,321,345]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
....................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D3AF937FFA0FA42FE9850FAF136" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1871" box="[1417,1482,321,345]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Physopyxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="627" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lyra">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF937FFA0FA42FE9850FAF136" box="[1417,1482,321,345]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">P. lyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F937FFA0FB94FEB850F9F116" blockId="2.[839,1482,194,377]" box="[1119,1481,354,377]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
(Amazon basin in 
<collectingCountry id="F34F7629F937FFA0FAD5FEB8507FF116" box="[1310,1359,354,377]" name="Peru" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F34F7629F937FFA0FAB4FEB850F2F116" box="[1407,1474,354,377]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Brazil</collectingCountry>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736B9F937FFA0FC8CFE7850F9F236" blockId="2.[839,1481,418,601]" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">
2'. Lateral plates with two or more series of spines; depth of superior wing of lateral plates equal to or less than that of inferior wing (
<figureCitation id="13632A3CF937FFA0FBC5FE38516FF196" box="[1038,1119,482,505]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[158,197,1919,1942]" captionTargetBox="[331,1310,622,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[321,1318,619,1904]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Diagnostic characters of the three species of Physopyxis. a. Physopyxis cristata; b. Physopyxis lyra; c. Physopyxis ananas; d. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. ananas and P. cristata; e. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. lyra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5418075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5418075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
); coracoid processes narrow and converging toward central axis of the body (
<figureCitation id="13632A3CF937FFA0FAF5FDD850BDF276" box="[1342,1421,514,537]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[158,197,1919,1942]" captionTargetBox="[331,1310,622,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[321,1318,619,1904]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Diagnostic characters of the three species of Physopyxis. a. Physopyxis cristata; b. Physopyxis lyra; c. Physopyxis ananas; d. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. ananas and P. cristata; e. ventral view of scapular girdle in P. lyra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5418075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5418075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Fig. 2d</figureCitation>
); adipose fin usually absent ........................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D3AF937FFA0FAACFDF850F9F256" authorityName="Sousa &amp; Rapp Py-Daniel" authorityYear="2005" box="[1383,1481,546,569]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Physopyxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="627" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ananas">
<emphasis id="B92CEAABF937FFA0FAACFDF850F9F256" box="[1383,1481,546,569]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">P. ananas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(widely distributed in Amazon and 
<collectingCountry id="F34F7629F937FFA0FAC3FD985047F236" box="[1288,1399,578,601]" name="Guyana" pageId="2" pageNumber="627">Essequibo</collectingCountry>
basins)
</paragraph>
